|       Method |      Mean |     Error |    StdDev | Ratio | RatioSD |
|------------- |----------:|----------:|----------:|------:|--------:|
|     Original |  6.431 ns | 0.0962 ns | 0.0803 ns |  1.00 |    0.00 |
| Deserialized | 10.424 ns | 0.2067 ns | 0.1832 ns |  1.62 |    0.04 |

The cause of the issue is that, we'll save `EqualityComparer<T>.Default` if the `_comparer` is `null`:

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/1083657c17b84248ea59896823f605ea63ce78a6/src/Common/src/CoreLib/System/Collections/Generic/Dictionary.cs#L358

But after deserialization we haven't set it back:

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/1083657c17b84248ea59896823f605ea63ce78a6/src/Common/src/CoreLib/System/Collections/Generic/Dictionary.cs#L689

So the `_comparer` in the deserialized dictionary will keep an instance of `EqualityComparer<T>.Default` which will go to slow branches every time we're going to use `_comparer`.

It can be verified in this way:

```csharp
var dict = new Dictionary<int, int>();

var formatter = new BinaryFormatter();
var stream = new System.IO.MemoryStream();
formatter.Serialize(stream, dict);

stream.Position = 0;
var dictCopy = (Dictionary<int, int>)formatter.Deserialize(stream);

var comparerField = typeof(Dictionary<int, int>).GetField("_comparer", BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.NonPublic);
var comparer = comparerField.GetValue(dictCopy);

// expected to be null, but get an GenericEqualityComparer<int> now.
Console.WriteLine(comparer); 
```

To fix the issue, we can simply set `_comparer` back to `null` if the deserialized comparer is `EqualityComparer<T>.Default`, as what I did when optimizing `HashSet<>`:

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/45466468dce20e578b05055f1abc7baab5570135/src/System.Collections/src/System/Collections/Generic/HashSet.cs#L487-L490

I can create a PR to fix the issue, but I also have a question about how we can verify this with unit test. The tricky part is that it cannot be verified via public API. Also, it has to be reproduced with `BinaryFormatter`, but I doubt it's accessible in `System.Collections.Tests` project.

Can you provide any thought on how I should write unit test for this issue in corefx?

